Peak Trump
----------

Tara Palmeri: What does a
political director do inside the White House?

=C2=A0

Bill Stepien: In most White Houses, there=E2=80=99s a focus on helping guid=
e the legislative agenda based on polling data and public sentiment. In a T=
rump White House, it=E2=80=99s quite different, as you might imagine. There=
=E2=80=99s a constant focus on races, candidates, and elections. My first t=
wo years with the president as political director were spent just
feeding information to him=E2=80=94not putting a finger on the scale of, =
=E2=80=9CSir, you should do this.=E2=80=9D People call him and talk about h=
ow great they are, or talk about how great their guy or gal is, without pro=
viding a full story. My job, as I saw it, was to provide a full political s=
tory of a race and give a full picture, so we could have our eyes wide open=
 on whatever political decisions he sought to make.

=C2=A0

Many
things are different eight years later. Most notably, his political strengt=
h is much more sizable. Now, you have people beating down the door because =
he=E2=80=99s at the height of his power. At any point, we would have died t=
o have the poll numbers and strength that he has right now.

=C2=A0

Trump=E2=80=99s down-ballot endorsements have had a spotty record=E2=80=94a=
nd he=E2=80=99s done some unusual ones. For instance, in the =E2=80=9922 Mi=
ssouri
Senate primary, he offered a kind of double endorsement to both Eric Schmit=
t and the scandal-plagued former governor Eric Greitens, and he=E2=80=99s d=
one this more than once. Usually, an endorsement is a golden ticket, but Tr=
ump doesn=E2=80=99t look at political capital that way.

=C2=A0

I think people oftentimes have a misguided view of the kind of person he ac=
tually is. At the end of the day, he=E2=80=99s a people pleaser. He
wants to make people happy. He wants to help people. He wants people to lik=
e him, and he wants to like people. The double-endorsement thing isn=E2=80=
=99t something I=E2=80=99d seen before, but it=E2=80=99s in line with him w=
anting to please and to help. That=E2=80=99s an example of him doing things=
 his own way, for sure.

=C2=A0

I think there are different ways to view political capital. Someone I used =
to work with would often say that you can
obtain political capital and keep it in your desk drawer to save and use fo=
r a later date=E2=80=94or you can use it and actually expend it for somethi=
ng you want or need. Trump views political capital in the latter category. =
He gets it. He uses it. And unlike anyone I=E2=80=99ve seen before, he can =
get more. I=E2=80=99m not sure anyone has really seen an unending supply of=
 political capital like Trump has, and I always laughed when I was in the W=
hite House and read stories about how he=E2=80=99d be enraged when one of
his endorsees lost a race. He sees these things as wins and losses. He=E2=
=80=99s very black and white in how he views these races and his decisions.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

And that extends to cabinet nominees, to legislation, to basically anything=
 he wants. It feels like everybody else is playing political chess, and he=
=E2=80=99s just like, Whatever=E2=80=A6

=C2=A0

He believes=E2=80=94and he=E2=80=99s right=E2=80=94that with a tweet or a p=
ress conference, the news media soaks it up. I don=E2=80=99t think he worri=
es too much about a bad news cycle, because it=E2=80=99s only a matter of h=
ours, not days or weeks with this guy. He=E2=80=99s using his levers of inf=
luence to negotiate, to push around, to get people to sit up in their chair=
s. That=E2=80=99s very different from what we=E2=80=99re used to from the p=
erson sitting in that office, but this is the guy.

=E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s Got 18
Months=E2=80=9D
----------------

Let=E2=80=99s talk about his legislative agenda. Senate leader John
Thune and Speaker of the House Mike Johnson see two different pathways to p=
assing Trump=E2=80=99s agenda. Johnson is arguing for one massive bill that=
 includes immigration, energy, and Trump=E2=80=99s tax code, while Thune is=
 saying they should push it through two bills. What are the pros and cons o=
f each approach?

=C2=A0

Candidly, I think they should ask Trump what he wants to do, because if he=
=E2=80=99s not involved
in the process, he=E2=80=99s less apt to engage. And we know he wants to be=
 engaged, because he loves this process of negotiation, having people in th=
e Oval Office going back and forth, battling it out. Besides, we know Trump=
=E2=80=99s instincts are really good on this.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Eight years ago, his instincts were to do tax cuts first, and all the smart=
 people in Washington said, Sir, we need to go after Obamacare first. That =
was the
white whale for Republicans in D.C., and it was more their fight than Presi=
dent Trump=E2=80=99s, and they ultimately wasted time on Obamacare. It didn=
=E2=80=99t go down as intended. It was weakening because of that swing and =
miss, and it took time to get back on track. So they should ask Trump what =
he wants to do, because who=E2=80=99s going to be a better salesman of this=
=E2=80=94Donald Trump, Senator Thune, or Speaker Johnson?=C2=A0

