ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong><em>Tara Palmeri</em></strong><strong>:=
 What does a
political director do inside the White House?</strong></p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
<em>Bill Stepien</em>: In most White Houses, there=E2=80=99s a focus on hel=
ping guide the legislative agenda based on polling data and public sentimen=
t. In a Trump White House, it=E2=80=99s quite different, as you might imagi=
ne. There=E2=80=99s a constant focus on races, candidates, and elections. M=
y first two years with the president as political director were spent just
feeding information to him=E2=80=94not putting a finger on the scale of, =
=E2=80=9CSir, you should do this.=E2=80=9D People call him and talk about h=
ow great they are, or talk about how great their guy or gal is, without pro=
viding a full story. My job, as I saw it, was to provide a full political s=
tory of a race and give a full picture, so we could have our eyes wide open=
 on whatever political decisions he sought to make.</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Man=
y
things are different eight years later. Most notably, his political strengt=
h is much more sizable. Now, you have people beating down the door because =
he=E2=80=99s at the height of his power. At any point, we would have died t=
o have the poll numbers and strength that he has right now.</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;"><strong>Trump=E2=80=99s down-ballot endorsements have had a spotty rec=
ord=E2=80=94and he=E2=80=99s done some unusual ones. For instance, in the =
=E2=80=9922 Missouri
Senate primary, he offered a kind of double endorsement to both Eric Schmit=
t and the scandal-plagued former governor Eric Greitens, and he=E2=80=99s d=
one this more than once. Usually, an endorsement is a golden ticket, but Tr=
ump doesn=E2=80=99t look at political capital that way.</strong></p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">I think people oftentimes have a misguided view of the kind of pe=
rson he actually is. At the end of the day, he=E2=80=99s a people pleaser. =
He
wants to make people happy. He wants to help people. He wants people to lik=
e him, and he wants to like people. The double-endorsement thing isn=E2=80=
=99t something I=E2=80=99d seen before, but it=E2=80=99s in line with him w=
anting to please and to help. That=E2=80=99s an example of him doing things=
 his own way, for sure.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I think there are different way=
s to view political capital. Someone I used to work with would often say th=
at you can
obtain political capital and keep it in your desk drawer to save and use fo=
r a later date=E2=80=94or you can use it and actually expend it for somethi=
ng you want or need. Trump views political capital in the latter category. =
He gets it. He uses it. And unlike anyone I=E2=80=99ve seen before, he can =
get <em>more</em>. I=E2=80=99m not sure anyone has really seen an unending =
supply of political capital like Trump has, and I always laughed when I was=
 in the White House and read stories about how he=E2=80=99d be enraged when=
 one of
his endorsees lost a race. He sees these things as wins and losses. He=E2=
=80=99s very black and white in how he views these races and his decisions.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
