ere bad. He looked at polls, but he was far from obsessed with them. He pai=
d attention when you had something to show him, but he was guided more by h=
is instinct than he was by a pollster=E2=80=99s number that was published s=
omewhere. He used polls to verify his instincts, but they weren=E2=80=99t
guiding his agenda or thought process.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-botto=
m:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>One of T=
rump=E2=80=99s greatest strengths is messaging. In his first term, he fired=
 off a flurry of executive orders that were pretty much toothless and could=
n=E2=80=99t be upheld in court. How much of this is Trump=E2=80=99s way of =
sending a message to the American people that he=E2=80=99s trying to make g=
ood on his promise, and if it fails, it=E2=80=99s not because of him?</stro=
ng></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">From my perspective, those are less legislative doc=
uments than they are guiding principles and shows of strength. They=E2=80=
=99re more, <em>I=E2=80=99m doing on Day One what I promised to do and what=
 you elected me to do</em>. Most Americans don=E2=80=99t know what the hell=
 an executive order is, or if something is subsequently held up in the cour=
ts, or overturned. They see him sitting at his desk with a big pen and a do=
cument with his
big signature on the piece of paper. And it=E2=80=99s the picture and messa=
ging that matters a whole lot more than what happens after. Candidly, peopl=
e are going to pay attention to what pictures they see on Day One.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;"><strong>Do you think Trump is genuinely eager to expand the pow=
er of the executive branch?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I don=E2=80=99t know the answer to
your question. I would say the thing he can do most to have expansive power=
s is continue to do what he=E2=80=99s doing right now. Right now, he=E2=80=
=99s so much stronger than he was eight years ago, when Americans gave him =
even marks and his approval rating was plus-one. Now, it=E2=80=99s approach=
ing <em>plus-20</em>. You can do a whole lot more with the bully pulpit whe=
n you=E2=80=99re strong politically. The best way to expand your powers is =
to look and be strong, and he is.=C2=A0</p></div>
